# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: clickjacking-defense
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:clickjacking-defense/clickjacking] Clickjacking is an instance of the confused deputy problem, wherein a computer is tricked into misusing its authority.
[src:clickjacking-defense/clickjacking] In 2002, it had been noted that it was possible to load a transparent layer over a web page and have the user's input affect the transparent layer without the user noticing.
[src:clickjacking-defense/clickjacking] However, fixes only started to trickle in around 2004, and the general problem was mostly ignored as a major issue until 2008.
[src:clickjacking-defense/clickjacking] In 2008, Jeremiah Grossman and Robert Hansen (of SecTheory) had discovered that Adobe Flash Player was able to be clickjacked, allowing an attacker to gain access to a user's computer without the user's knowledge.
[src:clickjacking-defense/clickjacking] Grossman and Hansen coined the term "clickjacking", a portmanteau of the words "click" and "hijacking".
[src:clickjacking-defense/clickjacking] As more attacks of a similar nature were discovered, the focus of the term "UI redressing" was changed to describe the category of these attacks, rather than just clickjacking itself.
[src:clickjacking-defense/clickjacking] One form of clickjacking takes advantage of vulnerabilities that are present in applications or web pages to allow the attacker to manipulate the user's computer for their own advantage.
[src:clickjacking-defense/clickjacking] For example, a clickjacked page tricks a user into performing undesired actions by clicking on concealed links.
[src:clickjacking-defense/clickjacking] On a clickjacked page, the attackers load another page over the original page in a transparent layer to trick the user into taking actions, the outcomes of which will not be the same as the user expects.
[src:clickjacking-defense/clickjacking] The unsuspecting users think that they are clicking visible buttons, while they are actually performing actions on the invisible page, clicking buttons of the page below the layer.
[src:clickjacking-defense/clickjacking] The hidden page may be an authentication page; therefore, the attackers can trick users into performing actions which the users never intended.
[src:clickjacking-defense/clickjacking] There is no way of tracing such actions to the attackers later, as the users would have been genuinely authenticated on the hidden page.
[src:clickjacking-defense/clickjacking] Classic clickjacking refers to a situation when an attacker uses hidden layers on web pages to manipulate the actions a user's cursor does, resulting in misleading the user about what truly is being clicked on.
[src:clickjacking-defense/clickjacking] A user might receive an email with a link to a video about a news item, but another webpage, say a product page on Amazon, can be "hidden" on top or underneath the "PLAY" button of the news video.
[src:clickjacking-defense/clickjacking] The user tries to "play" the video but actually "buys" the product from Amazon.
[src:clickjacking-defense/clickjacking] The hacker can only send a single click, so they rely on the fact that the visitor is both logged into Amazon and has 1-click ordering enabled.
[src:clickjacking-defense/clickjacking] While technical implementation of these attacks may be challenging due to cross-browser incompatibilities, a number of tools such as BeEF or Metasploit Project offer almost fully automated exploitation of clients on vulnerable websites.
[src:clickjacking-defense/clickjacking] Clickjacking may be facilitated by – or may facilitate – other web attacks, such as XSS.
[src:clickjacking-defense/clickjacking] Likejacking is a malicious technique of tricking users viewing a website into "liking" a Facebook page or other social media posts/accounts that they did not intentionally mean to "like".
[src:clickjacking-defense/clickjacking] The term "likejacking" came from a comment posted by Corey Ballou in the article *How to "Like" Anything on the Web (Safely)*, which is one of the first documented postings explaining the possibility of malicious activity regarding Facebook's "like" button.
[src:clickjacking-defense/clickjacking] According to an article in *IEEE Spectrum*, a solution to likejacking was developed at one of Facebook's hackathons.
[src:clickjacking-defense/clickjacking] A "Like" bookmarklet is available that avoids the possibility of likejacking present in the Facebook like button.
[src:clickjacking-defense/clickjacking] Nested clickjacking, compared to classic clickjacking, works by embedding a malicious web frame between two frames of the original, harmless web page: that from the framed page and that which is displayed on the top window.
[src:clickjacking-defense/clickjacking] This works due to a vulnerability in the HTTP header `X-Frame-Options`, in which, when this element has the value `SAMEORIGIN`, the web browser only checks the two aforementioned layers.
[src:clickjacking-defense/clickjacking] The fact that additional frames can be added in between these two while remaining undetected means that attackers can use this for their benefit.
[src:clickjacking-defense/clickjacking] In the past, with Google+ and the faulty version of `X-Frame-Options`, attackers were able to insert frames of their choice by using the vulnerability present in Google's Image Search engine.
[src:clickjacking-defense/clickjacking] In between the image display frames, which were present in Google+ as well, these attacker-controlled frames were able to load and not be restricted, allowing for the attackers to mislead whomever came upon the image display page.
[src:clickjacking-defense/clickjacking] CursorJacking is a UI redressing technique to change the cursor from the location the user perceives, discovered in 2010 by Eddy Bordi, a researcher at vulnerability.fr.
[src:clickjacking-defense/clickjacking] Marcus Niemietz demonstrated this with a custom cursor icon, and in 2012 Mario Heiderich did so by hiding the cursor.
[src:clickjacking-defense/clickjacking] Jordi Chancel, a researcher at Alternativ-Testing.fr, discovered a CursorJacking vulnerability using Flash, HTML and JavaScript code in Mozilla Firefox on Mac OS X systems (fixed in Firefox 30.0) which can lead to arbitrary code execution and webcam spying.
[src:clickjacking-defense/clickjacking] Different from other clickjacking techniques that redress a UI, MouseJack is a wireless hardware-based UI vulnerability first reported by Marc Newlin of Bastille.net in 2016 which allows external keyboard input to be injected into vulnerable dongles.
[src:clickjacking-defense/clickjacking] Logitech supplied firmware patches but other manufacturers failed to respond to this vulnerability.
[src:clickjacking-defense/clickjacking] In Browserless clickjacking, attackers utilize vulnerabilities in programs to replicate classic clickjacking in them, without being required to use the presence of a web browser.
[src:clickjacking-defense/clickjacking] This method of clickjacking is mainly prevalent among mobile devices, usually on Android devices, especially due to the way in which toast notifications work.
[src:clickjacking-defense/clickjacking] Because toast notifications have a small delay in between the moment the notification is requested and the moment the notification actually displays on-screen, attackers are capable of using that gap to create a dummy button that lies hidden underneath the notification and can still be clicked on.
[src:clickjacking-defense/clickjacking] CookieJacking is a form of clickjacking in which cookies are stolen from the victim's web browsers.
[src:clickjacking-defense/clickjacking] This is done by tricking the user into dragging an object which seemingly appears harmless but is in fact making the user select the entire content of the cookie being targeted.
[src:clickjacking-defense/clickjacking] From there, the attacker can acquire the cookie and all of the data that it possesses.
[src:clickjacking-defense/clickjacking] In fileJacking, attackers use the web browser's capability to navigate through the computer and access computer files in order to acquire personal data.
[src:clickjacking-defense/clickjacking] It does so by tricking the user into establishing an active file server (through the file and folder selection window that browsers use).
[src:clickjacking-defense/clickjacking] With this, attackers can now access and take files from their victims' computers.
[src:clickjacking-defense/clickjacking] Most managers did not protect against iFrame- and redirection-based attacks and exposed additional passwords where password synchronization had been used between multiple devices.
[src:clickjacking-defense/clickjacking] According to Google's "Browser Security Handbook" from 2008, NoScript's ClearClick is a "freely available product that offers a reasonable degree of protection" against Clickjacking.
[src:clickjacking-defense/clickjacking] Protection from the newer cursorjacking attack was added to NoScript 2.2.8 RC1.
[src:clickjacking-defense/clickjacking] The "NoClickjack" web browser add-on (browser extension) adds client-side clickjack protection for users of Google Chrome, Mozilla Firefox, Opera and Microsoft Edge without interfering with the operation of legitimate iFrames.
[src:clickjacking-defense/clickjacking] NoClickjack is based on technology developed for GuardedID.
[src:clickjacking-defense/clickjacking] The NoClickjack add-on is free of charge.
[src:clickjacking-defense/clickjacking] GuardedID (a commercial product) includes client-side clickjack protection for users of Internet Explorer without interfering with the operation of legitimate iFrames.
[src:clickjacking-defense/clickjacking] GuardedID clickjack protection forces all frames to become visible.
[src:clickjacking-defense/clickjacking] GuardedID teams with the add-on NoClickjack to add protection for Google Chrome, Mozilla Firefox, Opera and Microsoft Edge.
[src:clickjacking-defense/clickjacking] Gazelle is a Microsoft Research project secure web browser based on IE, that uses an OS-like security model and has its own limited defenses against clickjacking.
[src:clickjacking-defense/clickjacking] In Gazelle, a window of different origin may only draw dynamic content over another window's screen space if the content it draws is opaque.
[src:clickjacking-defense/clickjacking] The Intersection Observer v2 API introduces the concept of tracking the actual "visibility" of a target element as a human being would define it.
[src:clickjacking-defense/clickjacking] This allows a framed widget to detect when it's being covered.
[src:clickjacking-defense/clickjacking] The feature is enabled by default since Google Chrome 74, released in April 2019.
[src:clickjacking-defense/clickjacking] The API is also implemented by other Chromium-based browsers, such as Microsoft Edge and Opera.
[src:clickjacking-defense/clickjacking] Web site owners can protect their users against UI redressing (frame based clickjacking) on the server side by including a framekiller JavaScript snippet in those pages they do not want to be included inside frames from different sources.
[src:clickjacking-defense/clickjacking] Such JavaScript-based protection is not always reliable.
[src:clickjacking-defense/clickjacking] This is especially true on Internet Explorer, where this kind of countermeasure can be circumvented "by design" by including the targeted page inside an `<IFRAME SECURITY=restricted>` element.
[src:clickjacking-defense/clickjacking] Introduced in 2009 in Internet Explorer 8 was a new HTTP header `X-Frame-Options` which offered a partial protection against clickjacking and was adopted by other browsers (Safari, Firefox, Chrome, and Opera) shortly afterwards.
[src:clickjacking-defense/clickjacking] The header, when set by website owner, declares its preferred framing policy: values of `DENY`, `ALLOW-FROM *origin*`, or `SAMEORIGIN` will prevent any framing, framing by external sites, or allow framing only by the specified site, respectively.
[src:clickjacking-defense/clickjacking] In addition to that, some advertising sites return a non-standard `ALLOWALL` value with the intention to allow framing their content on any page (equivalent of not setting X-Frame-Options at all).
[src:clickjacking-defense/clickjacking] In 2013 the X-Frame-Options header has been officially published as RFC 7034, but is not an Internet standard.
[src:clickjacking-defense/clickjacking] The document is provided for informational purposes only.
[src:clickjacking-defense/clickjacking] The W3C's Content Security Policy Level 2 Recommendation provides an alternative security directive, frame-ancestors, which is intended to obsolete the X-Frame-Options header.
[src:clickjacking-defense/clickjacking] A security header like X-Frame-Options will not protect users against clickjacking attacks that are not using a frame.
[src:clickjacking-defense/clickjacking] The `frame-ancestors` directive of Content Security Policy (introduced in version 1.1) can allow or disallow embedding of content by potentially hostile pages using iframe, object, etc.
[src:clickjacking-defense/clickjacking] This directive obsoletes the X-Frame-Options directive.
[src:clickjacking-defense/clickjacking] If a page is served with both headers, the frame-ancestors policy should be preferred by the browser, although this requirement was ignored by older versions of some browsers.
[src:clickjacking-defense/framekiller] A **framekiller** (or **framebuster** or **framebreaker**) is a technique used by websites and web applications to prevent their web pages from being displayed within an HTML frame element.
[src:clickjacking-defense/framekiller] A frame is a subdivision of a Web browser window and can act like a smaller window.
[src:clickjacking-defense/framekiller] A framekiller is usually used to prevent a website from being loaded from within a frameset without permission, which might be part of an attack, as with clickjacking.
[src:clickjacking-defense/framekiller] Framekiller scripts have largely been replaced by the usage of `X-Frame-Options` and `Content-Security-Policy` headers, which prevent the page from being loaded in a frame in the first place.
[src:clickjacking-defense/framekiller] These headers are supported by all modern browsers and do not require the use of JavaScript.
[src:clickjacking-defense/framekiller] These headers are also intended to be specified inside the web server software, rather than directly inside the HTML.
[src:clickjacking-defense/framekiller] Framekillers are implemented using JavaScript that validates if the current window is the main window.
[src:clickjacking-defense/framekiller] This approach was proposed in 2010 by Gustav Rydstedt, Elie Bursztein, Dan Boneh and Collin Jackson in a paper that highlighted the limitations of existing frame-busting techniques along with techniques allowing to bypass them.
[src:clickjacking-defense/framekiller] An alternative choice is to allow the user to determine whether to let the framekiller work.
[src:clickjacking-defense/framekiller] The logic here was to display the page, but check if the top location is the same as the current page, and replace the top by current if not.
[src:clickjacking-defense/framekiller] This method however can be easily bypassed by blocking execution of the framebuster script from the outer frame.
[src:clickjacking-defense/framekiller] Client-side JavaScript solution relies on the end-user's browser enforcing their own security.
[src:clickjacking-defense/framekiller] This makes it a beneficial, but unreliable, means of disallowing your page to be embedded in other pages.
[src:clickjacking-defense/framekiller] The iframe in HTML5 has a sandbox attribute.
[src:clickjacking-defense/framekiller] The attribute's value is a set of allowed capabilities for the iframe's content.
[src:clickjacking-defense/framekiller] If the value is empty or not set, the iframe's content will not execute JavaScript, and won't allow top-level navigation.
[src:clickjacking-defense/framekiller] By specifying allow-scripts in the space separated set of exceptions in the value, the iframe will allow JavaScript, but will still disallow top-level navigation, rendering framekillers in the iframe impotent.
[src:clickjacking-defense/pointer-events] This feature is well established and works across many devices and browser versions.
[src:clickjacking-defense/pointer-events] It’s been available across browsers since July 2015.
[src:clickjacking-defense/pointer-events] The **`pointer-events`** CSS property sets under what circumstances (if any) a particular graphic element can become the target of pointer events.
[src:clickjacking-defense/pointer-events] The `pointer-events` property is specified as a single keyword chosen from the list of values below.
[src:clickjacking-defense/pointer-events] The element behaves as it would if the `pointer-events` property were not specified.
[src:clickjacking-defense/pointer-events] In SVG content, this value and the value `visiblePainted` have the same effect.
[src:clickjacking-defense/pointer-events] The element on its own is never the target of pointer events.
[src:clickjacking-defense/pointer-events] However its subtree could be kept targetable by setting `pointer-events` to some other value.
[src:clickjacking-defense/pointer-events] In these circumstances, pointer events will trigger event listeners on this parent element as appropriate on their way to or from the descendant during the event capture and bubble phases.
[src:clickjacking-defense/pointer-events] The element can only be the target of a pointer event when the `visibility` property is set to `visible` and when e.g., a mouse cursor is over the interior (i.e., fill) of the element.
[src:clickjacking-defense/pointer-events] The value of the `fill` property does not affect event processing.
[src:clickjacking-defense/pointer-events] The element can only be the target of a pointer event when the `visibility` property is set to `visible` and e.g., when the mouse cursor is over the perimeter (i.e., stroke) of the element.
[src:clickjacking-defense/pointer-events] The value of the `stroke` property does not affect event processing.
[src:clickjacking-defense/pointer-events] The element can be the target of a pointer event when the `visibility` property is set to `visible` and e.g., the mouse cursor is over either the interior (i.e., fill) or the perimeter (i.e., stroke) of the element.
[src:clickjacking-defense/pointer-events] The values of the `fill` and `stroke` do not affect event processing.
[src:clickjacking-defense/pointer-events] The value of the `visibility` property does not affect event processing.
[src:clickjacking-defense/pointer-events] The element can only be the target of a pointer event when the pointer is over the interior (i.e., fill) of the element.
[src:clickjacking-defense/pointer-events] The values of the `fill` and `visibility` properties do not affect event processing.
[src:clickjacking-defense/pointer-events] The element can only be the target of a pointer event when the pointer is over the perimeter (i.e., stroke) of the element.
[src:clickjacking-defense/pointer-events] The values of the `stroke` and `visibility` properties do not affect event processing.
[src:clickjacking-defense/pointer-events] The element can only be the target of a pointer event when the pointer is over the bounding box of the element.
[src:clickjacking-defense/pointer-events] The element can only be the target of a pointer event when the pointer is over the interior (i.e., fill) or the perimeter (i.e., stroke) of the element.
[src:clickjacking-defense/pointer-events] The values of the `fill`, `stroke`, and `visibility` properties do not affect event processing.
[src:clickjacking-defense/pointer-events] When this property is unspecified, the same characteristics of the `visiblePainted` value apply to SVG content.
[src:clickjacking-defense/pointer-events] In addition to indicating that the element is not the target of pointer events, the value `none` instructs the pointer event to go "through" the element and target whatever is "underneath" that element instead.
[src:clickjacking-defense/pointer-events] Note that preventing an element from being the target of pointer events by using `pointer-events` does *not* necessarily mean that pointer event listeners on that element *cannot* or *will not* be triggered.
[src:clickjacking-defense/pointer-events] If one of the element's children has `pointer-events` explicitly set to *allow* that child to be the target of pointer events, then any events targeting that child will pass through the parent as the event travels along the parent chain, and trigger event listeners on the parent as appropriate.
[src:clickjacking-defense/pointer-events] Of course any pointer activity at a point on the screen that is covered by the parent but not by the child will not be caught by either the child or the parent (it will go "through" the parent and target whatever is underneath).
[src:clickjacking-defense/pointer-events] Elements with `pointer-events: none` will still receive focus through sequential keyboard navigation using the Tab key.
[src:clickjacking-defense/pointer-events] This example disables pointer events (clicking, dragging, hovering, etc.) on all images.
[src:clickjacking-defense/pointer-events] This example disables pointer events on the link to `http://example.com`.
[src:clickjacking-defense/x-frame-options] The HTTP **`X-Frame-Options`** response header can be used to indicate whether a browser should be allowed to render the document in a `<frame>`, `<iframe>`, `<embed>` or `<object>`.
[src:clickjacking-defense/x-frame-options] Sites can use this to avoid clickjacking attacks and some cross-site leaks, by ensuring that their content is not embedded into other sites.
[src:clickjacking-defense/x-frame-options] If this header is not sent, and the website has not implemented any other mechanisms to restrict embedding (such as the `frame-ancestors` CSP directive), then the browser will allow other sites to embed this document.
[src:clickjacking-defense/x-frame-options] The document cannot be loaded in any frame, regardless of origin (both same- and cross-origin embedding is blocked).
[src:clickjacking-defense/x-frame-options] The document can only be embedded if all ancestor frames have the same origin as the page itself.
[src:clickjacking-defense/x-frame-options] Modern browsers that encounter response headers with this directive will ignore the header completely.
[src:clickjacking-defense/x-frame-options] The `Content-Security-Policy` HTTP header has a `frame-ancestors` directive which you should use instead.
[src:clickjacking-defense/x-frame-options] For more information, see the Microsoft support article on setting this configuration using the IIS Manager user interface.
